                    <physDesc>
                        <objectDesc>
                            <supportDesc>
                                <support><p><ref target="https://canmore.org.uk/site/38529/gigha-cnoc-na-carraigh">Canmore</ref> <idno type="Canmore">38529</idno></p>
                                    <material type="stone">Granite</material> 
                                    <objectType key="monument">Pillar</objectType>                                     
                                    <dimensions unit="m">                                         
                                            <height>1.7</height>
                                            <width>0.25 at base, 0.20 at the top</width>
                                            <depth>0.31 at base, 0.23 at the top</depth>
                                     </dimensions>         
                                </support>
                                <condition>A tall, square-shaped pillar, it <q>is unclear whether the monument is a re-used pre-historic standing stone or a pillar specially erected for the bearing of the inscription</q> (Forsyth 1996, 289). <q>The stone has fallen and been re-erected at least twice</q>, the first time it was intentionally toppled by some young men while the second fall was as a result of quarrying near the base on one side of the stone (ibid. 288-289). There is general weathering with <q>a series of four large, shallow, unevenly spced chunks missing from the ogham-bearing arris</q> (ibid. 290). The ogham inscription <q>which is worn and in a bad condition, is defaced by series of spalls on the arris</q> (ibid. 290). The portion of the inscription <q>nearest the ground is the most badly worn and the most disputed</q> (ibid. 291).
                                </condition>
                            </supportDesc>
                            <layoutDesc>
                                <layout>The ogham inscription is on the north west edge of the four-sided pillar stone and reads upwards from the bottom.
                                </layout>
                            </layoutDesc>
                        </objectDesc>
                        <handDesc>
                            <handNote>There is a wide range of published interpretations of the ogham that along with its general poor condition make a definitive reading difficult. On the same grounds, it is difficult to make definitive statements about its carving technique. <q>As they now survive, the strokes are finger-scale and with a U-section. Where it can be measured with any certainty the length of h-aicme strokes is about <height unit="mm">60</height></q> (Forsyth 1996, 291). The gaps between the letters most likely contained vowel notches now lost. Forsyth describes the Gigha inscription as <q>a classic Type Ia ogham with no drawn stem-line and vowels which are little more than nicks - the 'text-book' form of the script</q> (ibid. 295).
                            </handNote>
                        </handDesc>
